Summary
In this lab, we explored the uniq command in Linux and its application in analyzing customer purchase data. We learned how to:

Prepare data for use with uniq by sorting it first.
Use uniq to remove duplicate entries from a sorted file.
Use uniq -c to count occurrences of each unique line.
Use uniq -d to identify duplicate lines.
These skills are valuable for data analysis tasks, helping you to efficiently process and extract insights from large datasets.

Additional uniq command options not covered in this lab include:

-u: Display only unique lines (lines that appear exactly once)
-i: Ignore case when comparing lines
-f N: Skip the first N fields when comparing lines
-s N: Skip the first N characters when comparing lines
-c (--count): Prefixes lines by the number of occurrences.
-d (--repeated): Only prints duplicate lines (one for each group of repeated lines).
-D (--all-repeated): Prints all duplicate lines. It displays every instance of lines that appear more than once.
-u (--unique): Only prints lines that are not repeated (lines that appear exactly once).
-i (--ignore-case): Ignores case differences when comparing lines ("Apple" and "apple" would be treated as the same).
-f N (--skip-fields=N): Skips the first N fields (columns) on each line before comparing. Fields are separated by blanks or tabs.
-s N (--skip-chars=N): Skips the first N characters on each line before comparing.
-w N (--check-chars=N): Compares no more than N characters per line.
